                <fr:title text="The dual Rieger-Nishimura scheme">The dual Rieger-Nishimura scheme</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {S}[x]]]></fr:tex> be the free <html:em>coHeyting algebra</html:em> with one generator. By duality, since free distributive lattices are self-dual <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2[x]^{\mathrm {op}} \cong  2[x]]]></fr:tex>, we in fact have
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \mathbb {S}[x] \cong  \mathbb {H}[x]^{\mathrm {op}}, ]]></fr:tex>
  where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {H}[x]]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link href="/schm-LRJP/" title="The Rieger-Nishimura scheme" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-LRJP/" display-uri="schm-LRJP" type="local">Rieger-Nishimura</fr:link> algebra. This way, we can compute <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {S}[x]]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]]]></fr:tex> as below,
  
  <html:figure><fr:resource hash="d87a97748771c56fd782821194b49f10"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/d87a97748771c56fd782821194b49f10.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
    \begin {tikzcd}
      & {\mathbb {S}[x]} & {\mathrm {Spec}\,\mathbb {S}[x]} \\
      1 &&& \top  \\
      {1\backslash  x} & x & \vdots  & \vdots  \\
      {x \wedge  (1\backslash  x)} & {1\backslash  (1\backslash  x)} & \bullet  & \bullet  \\
      {x\backslash  (1\backslash  (1\backslash  x))} & {1\backslash  x \wedge  1\backslash  (1\backslash  x)} & \bullet  & \bullet  \\
      \vdots  & \vdots  & \bullet  & \bullet  \\
      & 0 & \bullet  & \bullet 
      \arrow [from=3-1, to=2-1]
      \arrow [from=3-2, to=2-1]
      \arrow [from=3-3, to=2-4]
      \arrow [from=3-4, to=2-4]
      \arrow [from=4-1, to=3-1]
      \arrow [from=4-1, to=3-2]
      \arrow [from=4-2, to=3-2]
      \arrow [from=4-3, to=3-3]
      \arrow [from=4-3, to=3-4]
      \arrow [from=4-4, to=3-4]
      \arrow [from=5-1, to=4-1]
      \arrow [from=5-2, to=4-1]
      \arrow [from=5-2, to=4-2]
      \arrow [from=5-3, to=4-3]
      \arrow [from=5-3, to=4-4]
      \arrow [from=5-4, to=3-3]
      \arrow [from=5-4, to=4-4]
      \arrow [from=6-1, to=5-1]
      \arrow [from=6-1, to=5-2]
      \arrow [from=6-2, to=5-2]
      \arrow [from=6-3, to=5-3]
      \arrow [from=6-3, to=5-4]
      \arrow [from=6-4, to=4-3]
      \arrow [from=6-4, to=5-4]
      \arrow [from=7-2, to=6-1]
      \arrow [from=7-2, to=6-2]
      \arrow [from=7-3, to=6-3]
      \arrow [from=7-3, to=6-4]
      \arrow [from=7-4, to=5-3]
      \arrow [from=7-4, to=6-4]
    \end {tikzcd}
  ]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:figure>

  <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]]]></fr:tex> is the union of two standard opens
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x] = \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]/ x \cup  \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]/ (1\backslash  x)]]></fr:tex>
  However, the interesting thing here is that their intersection is isomorphic to the total space again
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]/x \cap  \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]/(1\backslash  x) = \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]/(x \wedge  (1\backslash  x)) \cong  \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]. ]]></fr:tex>
  This seems to hint at a <html:em>coinductive</html:em> feature of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {S}[x]]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
